        "Balance-sheet shrinkage: raising cash by selling or pledging EXISTING assets — outright asset sales or repoing assets as collateral for a secured loan. Security-linked (this is Balance Sheet Liquidity, BSL): secured debt issuance, secured credit-line draws backed by pledged assets, and asset/repo sales.",
        "The three underlying source types used in the equations: AS (asset sales), RP (secured/repo funding using assets as collateral), and USF (unsecured funding — credit-line draws and interbank deposits). AS and RP shrink or hold constant the balance sheet; USF expands it."
