        "TSECCF: the CUMULATIVE running total of TSECF up to each date — ideally stays positive everywhere; going negative is a precursor to insolvency, the single most important number Treasury watches.",
        "TSLGC: how much liquidity could be generated (via LGC sources) by a given future date; TSCLGC is its cumulative running total.",
        "TSL0 (term structure of expected liquidity): TSECCF + TSCLGC combined — the true solvency test, since it asks whether the bank can cover a negative cumulated cash position once its actively-raisable liquidity is counted too. Must stay positive at every date to remain solvent.",
        "TSLaR (term structure of liquidity-at-risk): the unexpected cash-flow variation at each date, i.e. the gap between the average (expected) and the minimum (worst-case, at a chosen confidence level) cumulated cash-flow level — the VaR-style 'at risk' analog applied to liquidity rather than P&L.",
        "TSAA (term structure of available assets): tracks assets the bank actually POSSESSES (not necessarily owns) and can therefore use to generate liquidity — increased by reverse repo, buy/sellback, and security borrowing; decreased by repo, sell/buyback, and security lending."
