      name: "The full family of term structures",
      def: "TSECF/TSECCF (the maturity ladder): expected cash flows by date, and their cumulative running total — ideally stays positive at every date. TSL0 (term structure of expected liquidity): TSECCF plus TSCLGC combined, i.e. whether the institution can cover negative cumulated cash flows at a given date once its liquidity-generation capacity is counted too. TSLaR (term structure of liquidity-at-risk): unexpected cash flows at each date — the gap between the average and the minimum (worst-case, at a chosen confidence level) cumulated levels, the 'at risk' analog of VaR applied to liquidity.",
      pitfall: "A NEGATIVE TSECCF at some future date is a precursor to insolvency — the single most important number a Treasury department watches. Note that TSL0, not TSECCF alone, is the true solvency requirement, since TSL0 also credits the bank for liquidity it could actively raise.",
